          },
          {
            "type": "blockquote",
            "value": "Chris Pang started working out for a common reason: to get the girl. But his motives are a lot deeper than that now.<br/>‚Ä¶<br/>In <i>Crazy Rich Asians</i>, [Adele] Lim and co-writer Peter Chiarelli deliberately set out to depict Asian men as sexy and masculine. The movie seeks to accomplish this not by delving into serious subject matter like <i>The Joy Luck Club</i> (the last mainstream Hollywood movie to feature a mostly Asian cast), but by emphasizing the joy of being Asian ‚Äî and, in the case of Pang and Golding, the joy of being an attractive, fit Asian man.<br/>‚Äú[The movie shows] Asian men and the masculinity of Asian men, without needing to overdo it or overcompensating, without being heavy-handed,‚Äù says Ronny Chieng, who plays one of the film‚Äôs antagonists, Edison Cheng."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "I truly understand the sentiment. As someone situated in my body, however, I wonder whether Asian masculinity uproots White masculinity, or substitutes it, replacing it with an ideal similarly harmful at its core. A central aspect of masculinity is the positioning of one kind of male over another, like White men over men of color or heterosexual men over homosexual men. For Asian men and women, this domination has occurred through both asexualization and hyper-feminization (as opposed to the hyper-masculinization of Black men and women).<cite>Takinami</cite> In <i>Crazy Rich Asians</i> I saw an example of Asian masculinity that seems to rival White masculinity. But it reminded me of how I felt in history class when teachers lectured on the negative stereotypes that faced Asian male immigrants: they were diseased; they were corrupt; they were <i>effeminate</i>. Effeminacy was always treated as an insult. On Google, the word‚Äôs definition is literally stamped with the <span id=\"derogatory\"> DEROGATORY </span> box."
