          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In understanding as derogatory what the White man called the Asian-American man, and in trying to protest it with another form of masculinity, it seemed the Asian-American man was reproducing the same mechanism of power and control that has been used to subordinate them."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "As I insinuate that I think masculinity always has to subordinate others, I then must answer this: Who are the <i>Crazy Rich Asians </i>men, by being Asian but also hot and muscular, subordinating?"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "What first comes to mind is that, within the Chinese-American community, a clearly subjugated identity is homosexuality. Homosexuality is tabboo in my house, and I get the sense that it is broadly in Taiwan as well, though I don‚Äôt much about Taiwan. But I don‚Äôt think the intermale stigmatization that homophobia represents can be attributed, at least not much, to the ‚Äúprotest masculinity‚Äù that Asian-American men develop in America. Homophobia has its own fuel in the East.<cite>Eng</cite>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "One of the only Asian men I know to look up to is Áà∏Áà∏. But he grew up in Taiwan, and his ideas of manhood probably weren‚Äôt formed, or affected as much, in the United States. Thus I turn to <i>Chan is Missing</i> to try to better understand Asian-American masculinity. Early on in the film, we see signs that Steve‚Äôs cultural displacement ‚Äî born in America in a Chinese body ‚Äî has made him aggressive in his American identity."
          },
          {
