              "asset": "pants.mp4"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "That overt confidence, that mockery, that putting down of people more Chinese than you out of your own insecurity ‚Äî those are some sure markers of American masculinity. As Peter Feng writes<cite>Feng</cite> in ‚ÄúBeing Chinese American, Becoming Asian American‚Äù:"
          },
          {
            "type": "blockquote",
            "value": "Steve‚Äôs references to combat in Vietnam, not to mention his repeated use of the interjection \"man,\" hint at the threat to his masculine identity posed by Chan Hung. Chan Hung's inability to assimilate threatens Steve's perception of himself as American and as a man. (104)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "But this form of masculinity is different from the one in <i>Crazy Rich Asians</i>. Steve has directly adopted a White form of masculinity ‚Äî the one that puts down Asian men ‚Äî in an attempt to feel more secure about the instability of his own identity. In <i>Crazy RIch Asians</i>, I believe, the writers hoped to replace White masculinity with an Asian-American kind of masculinity."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Could Asian-American masculinity simply be a necessary form of resistance? Can Asian-American masculinity in the media co-exist with my feeling of needing to rid myself of masculinity? I wrote in my <a href=\"https://jsonkao.github.io/diaspora-puddle/\">midterm essay</a> that representation is indispensable, but inadequate. I feel the need to amend that to be, representation is indispensable <i>and</i> inadequate. The changed word implies that representation may not be an ideal that is ‚Äúnecessary but flawed‚Äù. It is necessary to break down harmful cultural ideas, yes. But that is a deconstruction that must coexist with a building-up process in which Asian males learn to look to something other than masculinity. Indispensable <i>and</i> inadequate."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "But if Chris Pang is shirtless in theaters everywhere, does that allow sufficient space for the building-up of Asian-American males? I remember in the seventh grade I was really into the K-pop group NU‚ÄôEST. I would watch their performances and reality show episodes all the time."
          },
          {
            "type": "code",
            "value": "<iframe width=\"700\" height=\"394\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/MwlKalNwGdk\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe><p class=\"caption\" style=\"color:#121212\">I could do this dance!</p>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Though he never directly said it, I could tell that Áà∏Áà∏ could get a bit uncomfortable with my K-pop phase. There was one NU‚ÄôEST member in particular that he disapproved of: Ren."
          },
